content.description: Start with you left hand on a small crystal and right hand on the arete. Move up facing the slab using the arete with your right. Nice top out lip.
content.location: Facing the slab, the trail will be off to your right.

content.description: Stand start to the right of "Ain't it Enough" with your left hand on W-shaped crimp rail and your right hand up on one of the high crimps. Head straight up to the slabby topout. All holds that connect to the left arete were not used.
Sit start with hands matched on the slanted rail. Head straight up from there using holds on the face.
content.location: This is low start to Jet Lag.

content.description: Start right with a right hand around the corner, a left hand on a sloper, a right foot smeared on the lower right corner, and a left foot up on the nice rail. Make a few quick moves up to the top. This is sort of a slab problem.
content.protection: A pad and A spotter. There is a single tree that looms behind you once you reach the middle/top of the route.
content.location: This is located on the same face as "Ain't it Enough". It starts on the rightmost corner of the block, though.

content.description: This is named after the geocache you can find under this boulder. Start standing on the arete. Move up and right until you can roll the lip. You could add a sit.
content.protection: This has a dicey landing. Four pads made it feel comfortable.
content.location: It is on the arete to the right of the slab section of the boulder.

content.description: Start matching on the W-shaped crimp and a right foot on a small nub. I found that I needed to get my right index finger in the middle of that "W". Pull up, and heel hook around the arete. Move up to nice crimp left, then match. Move your right foot high up to a small indent. Use the arete, and get your left foot up. Do an easy topout from there.
content.protection: A pad. It has a nice, flat landing.
content.location: With your back to the trail, it's to the left side of the boulder. There is no walkoff, you have to jump.

content.description: Start crossed with your left hand on a scoop-like crimp and right pinching just above. Set your feet and throw to a crimp out left. Find your way to the horn. Trend right to eventually top out at the bowl. Committing opening moves are fun!
content.protection: 2 pads is best to protect the big move.
content.location: It is on the backside of the block.

climbs.fa: Dan Knisell and Ryan Loiselle on 9/27/17

content.description: Start with both hands on nice jugs, located on top of the large flake. This might be quite the reach for a shorter climber. The flake sounds hollow, but don't be scared to put some weight on it. Use a good right foot to press out left, and either climb to the top statically or make a sweet dyno move!
content.protection: A pad and a spotter. The landing is on nice flat ground! There are a couple of small trees directly behind you.
content.location: This is to the right of "Above My Pay Grade."

content.description: This is a nice, small, slabby, very lonely granite block. The rock quality is very good and for a small boulder it holds several routes.
